//----------------------------------------

 when initial js loaded into browser , JS engine

 will create one 'Global Execution-Context' 


  Execution-Context --> memory that holds args,local var
                        with instructions to execute

  
  window === this

 --------------------------------------------------

  Global Execution-Context
  
     has 2 phases
     
     a. context-creation phase
     
        -->all variables are hoisted ( lifting-up ) to the top of context
           with default value ( undefined )
     	
     	-->all global variables are assigned as property of glob-obj ( window ). 
     
     b. context-execution phase

--------------------------------------------------------


  in JS , every func invocation will create one execution-context which
  is child of above context.

--------------------------------------------------------




  JS is
  
     -> single-threaded lang
     -> can provide better concurrency
     -> it will do non-blocking IO
     -> callback
     -> can execute functions asynch


How JS executes in browser ?


 e.g chrome browser
 
    1. JS-engine ( v8 )

       single-call-stack   ( to execute context )
       heap
       
    2. Web APIs ( e.g DOM , XHR , etc... )
    3. callback/message queue
    4. Event-Loop
    
    
  ----------------------------------------------     








